                                                                                                                                Charts

                                                                                                                                Charts is a global library for data visualization that provides reusable, flexible chart modules that can be used across all platforms and lines of business.

                                                                                                                                Usage
                                                                                                                                Charts by concepts
                                                                                                                                Chart colors
                                                                                                                                Base charts library

                                                                                                                                Why aren't we using our brand colors?

                                                                                                                                Brand colors usually possess a specific meaning or serve as a product's function. For example, Uber's safety blue is used only to communicate safety to the user. Meanwhile, Uber's black is our universal UI color used for most CTAs and buttons. If you use these colors to represent data not associated with these ideas or UI patterns, you could be creating an opportunity for confusion for the user.

                                                                                                                                At the same time, the visualization palette should fit into our brand world - and that's why three of the primary colors come directly from our global palette (Knoll Blue is Blue 300, Norman Yellow is Secondary Yellow, and Eames Navy is Blue 600).


                                                                                                                                Types of data

                                                                                                                                Categorical data

                                                                                                                                We frequently use color to distinguish discrete items or groups that do not have an intrinsic order, such as different countries on a map or different products. In this case, we use qualitative colors. For qualitative (categorical) data, it's important to have a balanced palette with a variety of lightness, hue, and saturation. So viewers can easily distinguish them from one another while also not creating a group of colors with a clear order or hierarchy - they should ideally be as equally distinct as possible. The more colors there are, the harder this becomes.

                                                                                                                                To future-proof the palette, we chose a mix of modern, bold colors that complement our bold data and ideas and lighter, pastel colors, which mimic our primary five palettes.

                                                                                                                                It's tricky to choose a well-balanced palette that's ageless and, at the same time, passes accessibility tests, like colorblind friendliness and background-text contrast. You can find more information about the accessibility of this palette below.


                                                                                                                                Numerical data

                                                                                                                                For numerical data, it's crucial to display the data with one color or related colors, like a scale that shows a low-to-high relationship. If you're not relying on the axes alone to convey numerical information, you can use color as a metaphor for low-to-high by using a color scale.

                                                                                                                                We have prepared two main types of scales for this very purpose: 1) Sequential and 2) Divergent. Sequential scales show a low-to-high relationship in your data and can have up to a few different analogous or related hues in the color transition. Diverging scales are best for comparing two variables, each with low-to-high values, with very distinctly different colors on the opposite poles to make comparison easy and neutral color in the middle. The neutral color often acts as a "0" between the two values. You will often see one color representing a negative set of values and the opposite color representing a positive set of values. However, the main goal of a diverging palette is to emphasize the extreme data points and deemphasize the less extreme data points with a neutral color.

                                                                                                                                Scales

                                                                                                                                Sequential

                                                                                                                                Sequential data classes are logically arranged from high to low, and sequential lightness steps should represent this stepped sequence of categories. Light colors usually represent low data values, and dark colors represent high values.

                                                                                                                                Step breakdown

                                                                                                                                Multi-hue sequential

                                                                                                                                Multi-hue sequential scales often leverage systematic lightness differences throughout the scheme; it’s not advisable to depend on a hue to impart the magnitude message. Use hue transitions to designate differences in proportions of the two variables mapped. For example, data on educational attainment crossed with crime rate categories are well represented by a sequential/sequential color scheme.

                                                                                                                                Step breakdown

                                                                                                                                Divergent

                                                                                                                                Diverging schemes allow the emphasis of quantitative data displays to be progressions outward from a critical midpoint of the data range. A typical diverging scheme pairs sequential schemes based on two different hues. They diverge from a shared light color - usually close to grey - for the critical midpoint toward dark colors of different hues at each extreme.

                                                                                                                                Accessibility

                                                                                                                                Color blindness

                                                                                                                                An estimated 8% of males and less than 1% of females have color vision problems.

                                                                                                                                Red-green color deficiency is the most common form of color blindness.

                                                                                                                                While there are many types of colorblindness, you can group them into three main groups: protanomaly, deuteranomaly, and tritanomaly.

                                                                                                                                • Protan - reduced sensitivity to red light

                                                                                                                                • Deutan - reduced sensitivity to green light

                                                                                                                                • Tritan - reduced sensitivity to blue light (very rare)

                                                                                                                                People who see color normally are called “Trichromatic” - meaning they can see all three types of cone photopigments normally. Colorblindness occurs when a human has abnormality or deficiencies in one of these cones.

                                                                                                                                Think of your eye as a camera. The front part has a lens. Its job is to focus images on the inside of the back of your eye. This area is called the retina. It’s covered with special nerve cells that contain pigments that react to light:

                                                                                                                                Cones control your color vision. There are several kinds of pigments present in three types of cone cells. Some react to short-wavelength light, others to medium wavelengths and others to higher wavelengths.

                                                                                                                                Rods only have one kind of pigment. It reacts the same way to any light wavelength. Rods don’t have anything to do with color vision, but they are very sensitive to light and allow us to see at night.

                                                                                                                                Test for colorblindness here: https://enchroma.com/pages/color-blindness-test?format1=numbers#test

                                                                                                                                Color FAQ's

                                                                                                                                In what order do I use these colors?

                                                                                                                                You should use the Primary and Secondary colors for most cases. Beyond that, you should use these colors from left to right (in the order they are laid out).

                                                                                                                                When do I use the primary colors?

                                                                                                                                We recommend using the qualitative primary five for most cases. You use the secondary palette only when you display more than 5 data on a chart or have a custom use-case.

                                                                                                                                The primary five should be your “go-to” colors for most charts and are very accessible as a group.

                                                                                                                                How did you develop the color scales?

                                                                                                                                Because the science of picking colors for each step in a scale is very precise, we used a color scale generator. It considers the perceptual difference (Delta E / ΔE00) between each step, color blindness accessibility, and gradual color-to-color transition.

                                                                                                                                Below is an example of what it looks like:

                                                                                                                                What is Delta E (ΔE00)?

                                                                                                                                Delta E is a metric for understanding how the human eye perceives color differences.

                                                                                                                                As a new guideline, we believe the optimal perceptual change is > 5, in general. If n=7, ΔE00 should not be less than 5. When n decreases, ΔE00 will increase. n= number of steps

                                                                                                                                Learn more here: http://zschuessler.github.io/DeltaE/learn/
